{
  "q1": {
    "assessment": "Yes for the ordering you described. The implementation does `currentSession < totalSessions` first, then checks `completedSessions[]`, then falls through to the ledger path.",
    "evidence": [
      "Count-mismatch early return is at line 36.",
      "Array-first branch is at lines 47-58.",
      "Ledger fallback is at lines 61-66.",
      "`currentSession` is type-checked as a number at line 33, so `.includes(sd.currentSession)` at line 48 uses strict equality against a known-number probe.",
      "`Array.isArray(sd.completedSessions)` at line 47 correctly rejects `null`, objects, strings, etc.; F5 covers `null` and object shapes at test lines 86-111."
    ],
    "issues": [
      {
        "issue": "The comment says `Returns false on any read/parse failure`, but ledger read failures do not actually behave that way.",
        "location": "Comment at lines 23-24 vs. `hasCloseoutEventForSession()` lines 77-80 and caller lines 62-64.",
        "fix": "Either weaken the comment, or change the helper to return a tri-state (`found` / `not found` / `unreadable`) so unreadable ledger data does not get treated as a definite missing closeout."
      }
    ]
  },
  "q2": {
    "assessment": "Yes. The warn is in the right semantic spot: only after the array has already established `closed`, and only when a present ledger disagrees.",
    "evidence": [
      "The warn is scoped to the array-satisfies branch at lines 47-58.",
      "It only fires when `session-events.jsonl` exists and lacks a matching closeout at lines 49-56.",
      "It does not fire for the no-ledger migration shape in F1 (test lines 29-41), which avoids warning on simple absence of a legacy signal.",
      "It also does not fire on the legacy no-array path, which avoids noise for pre-Set-022 sets."
    ],
    "issues": [
      {
        "issue": "Repeated reads of the same drifted set will emit the same warning every time.",
        "location": "Lines 53-56; there is no dedupe or rate limit.",
        "fix": "If Explorer refresh frequency is high, memoize once per `statePath/currentSession` or route through a logger with `warnOnce` semantics. Functionally this is harmless; it is only a noise concern."
      },
      {
        "issue": "Unreadable ledgers are indistinguishable from ledgers that truly lack the closeout, so the warn text can be misleading.",
        "location": "Lines 50-56 depend on `hasCloseoutEventForSession()`, which returns `false` on read error at lines 77-80.",
        "fix": "Use a tri-state helper or catch read errors separately and log a different message."
      }
    ]
  },
  "q3": {
    "assessment": "Coverage is good for the Set 023 reader change itself. F1-F7 plus the bonus fixture cover the main positive/negative branches and the audit-driven edge cases.",
    "evidence": [
      "F1 (lines 29-41): array includes `currentSession`, no ledger file, returns not-mid-set.",
      "F2 (lines 43-56): array misses `currentSession`, ledger also misses final closeout, downgrades.",
      "F3/F4 (lines 58-84): legacy no-array path, ledger positive and negative.",
      "F5 (lines 86-111): non-array `completedSessions` values fall through safely.",
      "F6 (lines 113-130): stray out-of-range entry does not accidentally satisfy `.includes(currentSession)`.",
      "F7 (lines 132-149): only `currentSession` matters; non-final disagreement is irrelevant.",
      "Bonus (lines 151-167): intended migration fix, array overrides a present ledger that lacks the final closeout."
    ],
    "issues": [
      {
        "issue": "The `currentSession < totalSessions` early-return path is not directly tested in this new suite.",
        "location": "Implementation line 36; no corresponding F-case in lines 29-167.",
        "fix": "Add one explicit fixture for `currentSession < totalSessions` to lock in the count-mismatch branch."
      },
      {
        "issue": "The suite does not assert the warning behavior itself.",
        "location": "Bonus test lines 151-167 only proves `no throw`; it does not spy on `console.warn`.",
        "fix": "Stub/spyon `console.warn` and assert: warned for the bonus shape, not warned for F1/F3/F4/F5."
      },
      {
        "issue": "An ambiguous shape is still untested: array present, array does not include `currentSession`, and no ledger file exists.",
        "location": "Implementation lines 47-66; not covered by F1-F7 or the bonus case.",
        "fix": "Add a fixture and decide the intended semantics explicitly. Today that shape returns `false` because lines 62-64 only downgrade when the ledger file exists."
      }
    ]
  },
  "q4": {
    "assessment": "Probably yes, but I cannot line-cite the docs because the edited doc text is not included inline here.",
    "evidence": [
      "The described schema-doc change—`completedSessions[]` authoritative for whether-closed, ledger authoritative for when-closed—is the right conceptual split.",
      "The close-out doc's new attestation note (`operator-attested` for migrated sets, `tool-maintained` for gated sets) is exactly the trust-model clarification this reader change needs."
    ],
    "issues": [
      {
        "issue": "The docs need to be careful not to overstate the implementation. The code still falls through to the ledger after an array miss.",
        "location": "Implementation lines 47-66; docs text not provided inline for direct citation.",
        "fix": "Document the reader algorithm in ordered steps/pseudocode, e.g. `count mismatch -> array-positive check -> ledger fallback`, and explicitly say `do not require both signals to agree`."
      }
    ]
  },
  "q5": {
    "assessment": "I agree with the change. This is the intended migration tradeoff, not a newly missed regression class.",
    "evidence": [
      "The new behavior only changes outcomes when the snapshot carries `completedSessions[]` and that array includes `currentSession` (lines 47-58).",
      "That is exactly the migrated/operator-attested scenario Set 023 is meant to honor.",
      "v0.13.12 had the opposite failure mode: false negatives (`Done` sets shown as `In Progress`) whenever the array was correct but the ledger was incomplete."
    ],
    "issues": [
      {
        "issue": "A false-positive `Done` classification is now possible if an operator manually adds an incorrect `currentSession` entry to `completedSessions[]`.",
        "location": "Array override branch at lines 47-58.",
        "fix": "No reader-side rollback is warranted if the spec explicitly trusts operator-attested migration arrays. Just keep that trust model explicit in docs. Note that the warning only helps when a disagreeing ledger file exists; no-ledger cases remain silent."
      }
    ]
  },
  "q6": {
    "assessment": "Three sharp edges remain worth calling out.",
    "issues": [
      {
        "issue": "Ledger read errors are treated as `missing closeout`, which can both misclassify and mis-warn.",
        "location": "`hasCloseoutEventForSession()` lines 77-80; callers at lines 50-56 and 62-64.",
        "fix": "Return a tri-state or throw a distinguishable error so `unreadable` is not conflated with `no closeout event present`."
      },
      {
        "issue": "The semantics for `completedSessions` present-but-missing-`currentSession` plus no ledger file are currently implicit and untested.",
        "location": "Lines 47-66; no direct test coverage in lines 29-167.",
        "fix": "Decide whether ledger absence means `unknown` or `negative` in that shape, then add a fixture to lock it in."
      },
      {
        "issue": "The new suite does not verify the observability contract itself.",
        "location": "Bonus test lines 151-167.",
        "fix": "Spy on `console.warn` and assert exact behavior for: warn-on-override, no-warn when ledger absent, no-warn on legacy paths."
      },
      {
        "issue": "Invalid numeric shapes are still accepted as long as they are `number`s.",
        "location": "Lines 33-34 only check `typeof === \"number\"`.",
        "fix": "If the schema requires positive integers and `currentSession <= totalSessions`, validate that explicitly or document that malformed numeric snapshots are left to higher layers."
      }
    ]
  }
}
